This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (which .NET 10 targets by default) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering, so `SoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` is fully ignored.

The modern replacement is reacting to **keyboard window-insets**. Here's the practical fix:

### 1. Set `AdjustResize` via the manifest (still needed as a hint)

In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`, ensure your main activity has:

```xml
android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"
```

### 2. Opt into edge-to-edge insets handling

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Let the app draw behind system bars / keyboard
    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    var rootView = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Use whichever is taller — keyboard or nav bar
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

        view.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

### 3. Your XAML (no special changes needed)

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (Android ≤ 14) | .NET 10 (Android 15+) |
|---|---|
| `AdjustResize` shrinks the window | Deprecated / no-op |
| System handles layout | App must read `Ime()` insets and apply padding itself |

The `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` inset reports the **exact keyboard height**. Setting that as bottom padding on the root view pushes your input bar up above the keyboard. When the keyboard dismisses, the inset returns to 0 and the padding clears.
